K.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":3,"post_id":17600,"edited":false,"creation_date":1400868522,"comment_id":24099,"body":"But the nicking isn&#39;t carried out by a restriction endonuclease but by a specific protein which remains linked to the 5&#39; end of the DNA. If this was accomplished by an R-M system on the phage the site would presumably be modified to protect it from double-stranded cutting."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4dded251881d6c2e6195d81cfc465e35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5006,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5006/adam-r","reputation":237,"display_name":"adam.r"},"score":0,"post_id":17600,"edited":false,"creation_date":1400873519,"comment_id":24101,"body":"I generally think of REs as producing double-stranded cuts. If I understand correctly, this answer only applies to those that create single-stranded cuts. Are they also called RE?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"post_id":17600,"edited":false,"creation_date":1400912683,"comment_id":24104,"body":"i just wonder which has an older origin- CRISPR-Cas or RE?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LnfsA.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3061,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3061/yummyclaypot","reputation":575,"display_name":"yummyclaypot"},"score":0,"post_id":17600,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1405886270,"comment_id":29419,"body":"@WYSIWYG Interesting question. Nearly all bacteria have a restriction modification system yet only about half have CRISPR/Cas. In archaea, CRISPR/Cas is more ubiquitous. Ancient ancestry and horizontal gene transfer make it difficult to make strong conclusions on which came first. CRISPR/Cas is interesting in that it requires an RNA co-factor (crRNA/tracrRNA). There may have existed (or still exists) an ancient CRISPR system that functioned without Cas or other proteins (e.g. an endonucleolytic ribozyme with a targeting domain that existed before the evolution of protein synthesis)."}],"down_vote_count":2,"last_activity_date":1400861095,"creation_date":1400860251,"body":"<p>If you have a dsDNA genome and replicate it by rolling circle like most bacteriophages and many plasmids do, an endonuclease is pretty much a necessity. <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/hiycs.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":17600,"question_id":17597,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1400861095},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1400868646,"creation_date":1400868646,"body":"<p>The familiar restriction enzyme EcoRI is plasmid encoded.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Betlach et al. (1976) A restriction endonuclease analysis of the bacterial plasmid controlling the EcoRI restriction and modification of DNA. Fed. Proc. 35:2037 - 43.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>For an example of a phage encoded system see:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Dempsey et al. (2005) Sau421, a BcgI-like restriction-modification system encoded by the Staphylococcus aureus quadruple-converting phage Phi42. Microbiology 151: 1301-1311<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This second paper suggests an answer to why a phage would have such a system: lysogens of Phi42 are resistant to infection by all 23 members of a standard set of <em>S. aureus<\/em> phages. Once a phage has lysogenised it is in its interest to prevent lysis of its host.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17604,"question_id":17597,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4dded251881d6c2e6195d81cfc465e35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5006,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5006/adam-r","reputation":237,"display_name":"adam.r"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1400875572,"creation_date":1400875131,"body":"<p>There are many proposals for the ecological role of restriction-modification (RM) systems, and why they would exist on mobile genetic elements (e.g. plasmids and viruses). In this case, I am specifically talking about the viruses that infect bacteria (aka, bacteriophage).<\/p>\n\n<p>1) RM systems may have an anti-viral function. Normally we would think of such systems as being part of the host chromosome, but as Alan Boyd suggested, once a temperate phage has integrated itself into the chromosome, its fitness is tied to its host. Therefore, a RM system found in a prophage could prevent infections by additional phage. See here for a discussion of this issue:\n<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23471617\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23471617<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>2) RM systems may have \"addictive\" properties by acting as toxin-antitoxin systems. Basically, this means that if the genes for the RM system are lost, the host cell dies. This can provide selection for the maintenance of plasmids and prophage inside of the host cell. See here for a discussion of this issue:\n<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3874152/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3874152/<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>3) Finally, viruses need to destroy the host genome -- both to suppress any anti-viral response and to release nutrients for viral replication. While this is typically achieved with nucleases other than restriction endonucleases, there is at least one situation where a RE seems to be involved. This is discussed in the first link above (see the section entitled \"Role in Nutrition\")<\/p>\n","answer_id":17605,"question_id":17597,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1400875572}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17597/restriction-endonucleases-are-found-in","last_activity_date":1400875572,"creation_date":1400854517,"answer_count":3,"title":"Restriction endonucleases are found in?","body":"<p>Quoting from : Scientific American July 1975 <em>The Manipulation of genes<\/em> by Stanley Cohen :<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Restriction endonucleases (and modification methylases) are widespread\n  in microorganisms; genes for <strong>making<\/strong> them were found on <strong>viral\n  chromosomes<\/strong> and extrachromosomal plasmid DNA as well as on many\n  bacterial chromosomes.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Why would the genes for making RE be found on viral chromosomes ? Also, could you give some examples where they are found on plasmids ?<\/p>\n","question_id":17597,"tags":["bacteriology","molecular-genetics","virus","plasmids","restriction-enzymes"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":17605,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":131,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Gtf1q.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6019,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6019/ermanen","reputation":80,"display_name":"ermanen"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5754/jarlemag","reputation":3075,"display_name":"jarlemag"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://