n perspective. I am unfamiliar with dinosaur taxonomy, but I was just making the point that birds being nested in the dinosaur clade doesn&#39;t necessarily imply that they <b>are<\/b> dinosaurs. I think the answer has to explicitly mention the claim that dinosaurs are monophyletic."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4690b9a0df8a4c1e35c088b077942e6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6132/steve-jessop","reputation":320,"display_name":"Steve Jessop"},"score":0,"post_id":17549,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0b71965060589f5ceb354c5daa347cc5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4112/sparhawk","reputation":103,"display_name":"Sparhawk"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1400830458,"comment_id":24077,"body":"@Sparhawk: sure, I think statements like &quot;views all organisms as interrelated in a nested set of monophyletic groups (clades)&quot;, are intended to make the more general claim that clades are the only groups used in formal classification and hence dinosaurs <i>necessarily<\/i> must be a clade if it&#39;s a classification at all. This is what cladists want us to believe, that there&#39;s no taxon to describe what you study and you should come out and call it &quot;radishes, emus and spanners&quot; or whatever ;-)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0b71965060589f5ceb354c5daa347cc5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4112/sparhawk","reputation":103,"display_name":"Sparhawk"},"score":0,"post_id":17549,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4690b9a0df8a4c1e35c088b077942e6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6132,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6132/steve-jessop","reputation":320,"display_name":"Steve Jessop"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1400850413,"comment_id":24086,"body":"@SteveJessop Oops. I totally missed that quote. Good point."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1400805980,"creation_date":1400691054,"body":"<p>Birds are both flying dinosaurs <em>and<\/em> flying reptiles. Yes, that's potentially confusing.<\/p>\n\n<p>To understand the apparent contradiction, you have to understand how modern classification of organisms works (<a href=\"http://www.ucmp.berkeley.edu/clad/clad4.html\">phylogenetic systematics<\/a>). Under the old (Linnean) classification system, Reptilia (reptiles) was an order and Aves (birds) was a separate order. Phylogenetic systematics, which has completely replaced the Linnean system, views all organisms as interrelated in a nested set of <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14877/birds-and-dinosaurs/14878#14878\">monophyletic<\/a> groups (clades). It's like a set of venn diagrams, where all organisms fall into a giant circle and then successively smaller circles classify more and more specific groups.<\/p>\n\n<p>The clade Reptilia includes snakes, lizards, crocodiles, and lots of extinct groups, including dinosaurs. So all dinosaurs are reptiles. The clade Dinosauria includes all the extinct dinosaurs (<em>Stegosaurus<\/em>, <em>Triceratops<\/em>, sauropods, etc.), including theropod dinosaurs, which include well known dinosaurs like <em>Tyrannosaurus<\/em> and <em>Allosaurus<\/em>. Based on a mountain on anatomical evidence, including lots of transitional fossils, living <a href=\"http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/article/evograms_06\">birds are a sub-group of theropod dinosaurs<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>So all birds (Aves) are theropod dinosaurs (Dinosauria: Theropoda). All dinosaurs are reptiles. Therefore, birds are dinosaurs and reptiles. They are just more closely related to dinosaurs than to other reptiles.<\/p>\n\n<p>The tricky part is that most people have an intuitive idea of what \"reptiles\" and \"dinosaurs\" are. To a systematist, whose job it is to classify organisms, these terms don't mean the same thing as they do to most people. Systematists think about groups like Reptilia and Dinosauria and how those groups are related to one another. So they have no problem saying that birds are dinosaurs <em>and<\/em> reptiles, because birds are nested within both of those groups.<\/p>\n\n<h3>A few words about pterosaurs<\/h3>\n\n<p>Along with birds and bats, pterosaurs are the other clade of vertebrates capable of powered, flapping flight. Pterosaurs fall within Reptilia (and Diapsida and Archosauria) along with Dinosauria, which includes birds. There are a lot of other extinct lineages in the tree that are not shown, e.g., ornithodirans that are not dinosaurs and not pterosaurs. Pterosaurs and birds share anatomical features that all reptiles, diapsids, archosaurs, and ornithodirans have, which is how we know that they are more closely related to each other than to other groups, like crocodiles. But their flight structures evolved independently and are anatomically distinct fro one another. So pterosaurs <em>are<\/em> flying reptiles but <em>not<\/em> flying dinosaurs.<\/p>\n\n<p>These images might help you understand the above explanation.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/nPg3f.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/MpU6G.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":17549,"question_id":17546,"up_vote_count":36,"last_edit_date":1400805980},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/cWBJh.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6800,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6800/sqb","reputation":206,"display_name":"SQB"},"score":17,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1400813469,"creation_date":1400742185,"body":"<p>In addition to <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/a/17549\">kmm's excellent answer<\/a>, I'd like to present <a href=\"http://xkcd.com/1211/\">the xkcd point of view<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/birds_and_dinosaurs.png\" alt=\"xkcd/1211\" title=\"Sure, T. rex is closer in height to Stegosaurus than a sparrow. But that doesn't tell you much; 'Dinosaur Comics' author Ryan North is closer in height to certain dinosaurs than to the average human.\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":17564,"question_id":17546,"up_vote_count":17,"last_edit_date":1400813469}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17546/were-there-any-flying-dinosaurs","last_activity_date":1400856143,"creation_date":1400688782,"answer_count":3,"title":"Were there any flying dinosaurs?","body":"<p>I've seen some articles which came in contradiction with each other.<\/p>\n\n<p>The first article was talking about flying dinosaurs, dinosaurs with feathers and so on.<\/p>\n\n<p>A couple of other articles are talking about misconceptions about dinosaurs one of them being that there are no flying dinosaurs but just flying reptiles (from <a href=\"http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/article/dinosaurs-flying-reptiles\">scholastic.com<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.livescience.com/24071-pterodactyl-pteranodon-flying-dinosaurs.html\">livescience.com<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>So, which one is right?\nAlso if possible please provide a source for argument.<\/p>\n\n<p>I cannot find the first article again.<\/p>\n","question_id":17546,"tags":["evolution","ornithology","palaeontology","herpetology"],"score":20,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3597,"up_vote_count":20,"last_edit_date":1400856143},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5b87af3621bd16385a386558b32644e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6821/mohamad","reputation":106,"display_name":"Mohamad"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550973bfc1f6c08ff29efee9a1cc7fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2938,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2938/jack-aidley","reputation":3478,"display_name":"Jack Aidley"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1400852462,"creation_date":1400852462,"body":"<p>The body needs more than energy to survive.<\/p>\n\n<p>Salt is vital to the body's function. Ions of sodium and calcium perform numerous vital functions, but are particularly related to the function of the nervous system and contraction of muscles. Accordingly, seeking out sources of salt makes sense in a natural environment in which salt is relatively unavailable.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17595,"question_id":17594,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17594/what-is-the-evolutionary-reason-behind-human-preference-for-salty-foods","last_activity_date":1400855547,"creation_date":1400851940,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the evolutionary reason behind human preference for salty foods?","body":"<p>It's been established that <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9216570\" rel=\"nofollow\">food palatability is related to it's caloric density<\/a>. This hypothesis is used to explain why humans are partial to sugar and fat. But it is also said that humans are partial to salt.<\/p>\n\n<p>Given that salt has no calories, are there evolutionary reasons that explain why humans have a preference for salty foods?<\/p>\n","question_id":17594,"tags":["evolution","food","diet"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":124,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/add6b6106e59fdda6da67863b256176f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5284,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5284/ryetochondria","reputation":86,"display_name":"ryetochondria"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users