there and are used for seeing in dark. But as we have evolved we cannot differentiate objects just based on their heat signatures. So just infrared vision wont be good."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2442ea911c89187262d6575d739a1ca7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5148,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5148/swbarnes2","reputation":1824,"display_name":"swbarnes2"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4baed26d9b00bbc7c0c706515aeb596e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8402,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8402/phresnel","reputation":101,"display_name":"phresnel"},"score":0,"post_id":16786,"edited":false,"creation_date":1405953760,"comment_id":29488,"body":"My eyes are not warm. Air does not reflect infrared light (you don&#39;t see an infrared aura around warm objects in infrared captures). Therefore, I could implant infrared sensors into my eyes without seeing myself all the time. And even if, the self-ambiance could still be subtracted out. And cold-blooded animals are not cold all the time, especially not after a sun bath."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1398204328,"creation_date":1398204328,"body":"<p>Infrared light is emitted by warm things, like our head.  We'd be detecting it ambiantly all the time.  That's why animals that can detect infrared are not warm-blooded.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16786,"question_id":16785,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/15894a0d103ab92a2cd3b1000efca418?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6422,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6422/cornelius","reputation":6008,"display_name":"Cornelius"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/79614cc5fcd376b95171a5c8f6354e8a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"register