es in our eyes to process infrared light, would someone with these 'special' eyes be able to see better than someone with 'regular' eyes? What would they see? What about in low-light conditions?<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/A3Xnw.jpg\" alt=\"Example of what I am talking about:\"><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>...Infra-red illumination of the eye produces the 'bright pupil' effect\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Source: <a href=\"http://www.museumsandtheweb.com/mw2003/papers/milekic/milekic.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.museumsandtheweb.com/mw2003/papers/milekic/milekic.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>(most of the way down the page)<\/p>\n","question_id":16785,"tags":["human-anatomy","human-eye"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":334,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1398208131},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Xqey0.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6617/tir38","reputation":143,"display_name":"tir38"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Xqey0.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6617/tir38","reputation":143,"display_name":"tir38"},"score":0,"post_id":17171,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399411535,"comment_id":23412,"body":"That first pic. That&#39;s what I saw. Thanks."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1399322087,"creation_date":1399322087,"body":"<p>It sounds pretty much like a fox squirrel (or better: as masked face fox squirrel which are found in Alabama).\nThey look like this (taken from this <a href=\"http://gardeningsoul.blogspot.de/2011/05/masked-face-fo