g/wiki/Ototoxicity\" rel=\"nofollow\">ototoxicity<\/a> and then also read these two papers which are both freely available (the figure above is from the first):<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21799993\" rel=\"nofollow\">Intracellular mechanisms of aminoglycoside-induced cytotoxicity.<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22715386\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gentamicin rapidly inhibits mitochondrial metabolism in\nhigh-frequency cochlear outer hair cells.<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>To answer the question why this occurs in the ear, it seems that there is some genetic predisposition for this, see this paper: \"<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17266591\" rel=\"nofollow\">Aminoglycoside-induced ototoxicity.<\/a>\" Mitochondrial damages leading to hearing loss is also not uncommin, see <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1376819/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>. Noise seems to play an additional role here and is probably the \"last drop\" to cause hearing loss.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17535,"question_id":17487,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1400744299}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17487/how-can-antibiotics-damage-the-ear","last_activity_date":1400744299,"creation_date":1400367345,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can antibiotics damage the ear?","body":"<p>What is the mechanism by which <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aminoglycoside\">aminoglycoside<\/a> antibiotics (such as streptomycin and gentamicin) damage the mechano-sensory hair cells of the auditory and vestibular system? (Could this be seen as evidence for <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20203251\">Lynn Margulis' theory that these cilia are descended from bacteria<\/a>?) <\/p>\n","question_id":17487,"tags":["antibiotics","hearing","human-ear","cilia"],"score":9,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":240,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1400600514},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grav