aphics output are quite publication friendly. I'm not an expert at it and I've only been playing around with it for a bit but when you get the hang of it, it's quite nice graphically. Although the VDW view is still space fill 3D but it's a bit nicer as it has opacity etc etc. Just download it and as soon as you open it up, you are presented with an example alignment and Jmol view. Just play around with the alignment section and the Jmol view and see if you like the aesthetics. The only tricky part in the software is getting the residues you want selected but once you manage that, you can get the program to display VDW only for the selected residues.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hope this helps.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17442,"question_id":17391,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1400161336}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17391/color-van-der-waals-bonds-in-swiss-pdbviewer","last_activity_date":1400161336,"creation_date":1399975078,"answer_count":1,"title":"Color van der waals bonds in swiss PdbViewer","body":"<p>I'm trying to color certain amino acid's van der waals bonds as in the following picture:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Vogl9.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>can anybody please describe the steps to accomplish that? <\/p>\n","question_id":17391,"tags":["bioinformatics","proteins","pdb"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":17442,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":135,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39e2199f9782b9b9abab588071c20e68?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6488,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6488/suresh-koya","reputation":122,"display_name":"Suresh Koya"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/41CJK.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5762,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5762/the-last-word","reputation":4553,"display_name":"The Last Word","accept_rate":100},"score"