t of that receptor such as montelukast can reduce their effect.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IgE\" rel=\"nofollow\">IgE<\/a> is involved in allergic responses because it interacts with Fc receptors on the surface of certain cells such as mast cells. If the IgE molecules are associated with one another through Ig-antigen interactions this leads to clustering of the Fc receptors which triggers an intracellular signalling pathway leading to mast cell degranulation - the release of histamine by fusion of storage vesicles with the cell membrane (i.e. exocytosis). <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histamine\" rel=\"nofollow\">Histamine<\/a> causes constriction of the bronchioles via effects on smooth muscle, just like leukotrienes.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17307,"question_id":17305,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17305/what-is-the-effect-of-montelukast-on-the-amount-of-ige-in-blood","last_activity_date":1399734182,"creation_date":1399721890,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the effect of Montelukast on the amount of IgE in blood?","body":"<p>I know that it decreases the amount of leucotrienes in blood.\nI saw a patient with high IgE altough under Montelukast medication.\nThis suggests me that Montelukast does not affect the immunoglobulins, but somehow restrict the allergic reaction indirectly.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the effect of Montelukast on the amount of IgE in blood?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":17305,"tags":["pharmacology"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":17307,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":368,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/QarBg.png?s=128&g=1","user_ty