h to contact a blood donation organisation for more specific information on how they handle &amp; categorise the blood.<\/p>\n\n<p>But using just RhD and ABO gives 8 combinations, positive and negative of A, B, AB, and O. You can find out more about the blood groups, blood donation, and the characteristics of blood groups <a href=\"http://www.blood.co.uk/about-blood/blood-group-basics/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>The subgroups you allude to are due to differences in the number of the antigens on the surface of the blood cell, for example the <a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20080802232301/http://www.owenfoundation.com/Health_Science/Blood_Group_A_Subtypes.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">A1 group have ~1,000,000 A antigens per cell whereas A2 variants have ~250,000<\/a>. The A group has ~20 subgroups, the vast majority of people are A1 (~80%) or A2 (~20%), and the other groups make up less than 1% of the population.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ABO_blood_group_system\" rel=\"nofollow\">These two subgroups are interchangeable as far as transfusion is concerned, but complications can sometimes arise in rare cases when typing the blood.<\/a><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":17275,"question_id":17271,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1399638503},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c4592aaf5a53444f1db92fa4a33c0308?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6517,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6517/adrienne","reputation":590,"display_name":"Adrienne"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Yhd3l.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6669,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6669/mayeenul-islam","reputation":106,"display_name":"Mayeenul Islam"},"score":0,"post_id":17283,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399663972,"comment_id":23543,"body":"Thanks. And, <i>And be aware that the average person